  2. Indexing (src/indexing/indexing.py)

  Data structure

  The index is stored in SQLite with five tables:

  ┌──────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │    Table     │                     Contents                     │
  ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ body_index   │ term, doc_id, frequency, positions (binary blob) │
  ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ title_index  │ term, doc_id, frequency                          │
  ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ author_index │ term, doc_id, frequency                          │
  ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ doc_lengths  │ doc_id, body_len, title_len, author_len          │
  ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ metadata     │ doc_id, title, author, language                  │
  └──────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Why SQLite instead of in-memory?

  With ~70,000 books, a full in-memory inverted index would require several GB of RAM.
  SQLite allows the index to live on disk and be queried on demand. B-tree indexes on the
  term column make lookups fast (O(log n)).

  Why store positions in the body index?

  Positions (token offsets within a document) enable phrase search — verifying that query
  terms appear consecutively in a document. This is stored as a compact binary array
  (array.array('I'), unsigned ints, 4 bytes each) rather than a Python list, reducing
  storage by ~7×.

  Why batch inserts?

  Instead of committing after each document, rows are accumulated in memory and flushed
  every 500 documents. A single executemany + commit is orders of magnitude faster than
  70,000 individual commits. SQLite pragmas WAL and synchronous=NORMAL further reduce write
   overhead.

  Why only index has_text=TRUE entries?

  Project Gutenberg metadata contains audio books, image collections, and other non-text
  formats. These have has_text=FALSE in the CSV and have no .txt file to index.

