  3. Three Retrieval Models

  All three models search the same three fields (title, author, body) and combine field
  scores using weights:

  ┌────────┬────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Field  │ Weight │                              Reason                               │
  ├────────┼────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ title  │ 3.0    │ A query term in the title is the strongest signal                 │
  ├────────┼────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ author │ 2.0    │ Author name match is very relevant                                │
  ├────────┼────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ body   │ 1.0    │ Body matches are weaker — any document mentioning a word once     │
  │        │        │ qualifies                                                         │
  └────────┴────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  For title and author queries, stopwords are removed from the query (using
  preprocess_field) to match how those fields were indexed.
  For body queries, stopwords are kept in the query (raw tokeniser, no stopword removal) to
   match how the body was indexed — this is what allows "to be, or not to be" to return
  results.

  ---
  Model 1: Structured Search (structured_search.py)

  Formula:
  score(q, d) = Σ_field [ weight_field × Σ_t ( tf(t,d,field) / field_len(d) ) ]

  What it does: For each query term in each field, divides the raw term frequency by the
  field length (number of tokens). This gives a normalised frequency — a term appearing 10
  times in a 100-token title scores the same as one appearing 100 times in a 1000-token
  body.

  Why no IDF? The structured model is intentionally simple. It ranks purely by how often
  query terms appear relative to document length, across all fields. There's no
  penalisation for common terms. This is the baseline model.

  Advantage: Favours short, focused documents where query terms are dense.
  Disadvantage: Common terms ("the", "and") aren't penalised even in body search — but this
   is partly mitigated by stopword removal for title/author.

  ---
  Model 2: Vector Space Model — VSM (vsm_search.py)

  Formula:
  TF  = log(1 + tf(t, d, field))          ← log normalisation
  IDF = log((N + 1) / (df + 1)) + 1       ← smooth IDF
  doc weight  = TF × IDF
  query weight = IDF  (tf = 1 in query)
  score(q, d) = Σ_field [ weight_field × Σ_t doc_weight × query_weight / sqrt(field_len) ]

  What it does: Each document and query is represented as a vector in term space. The score
   is the dot product of the query vector and document vector, normalised by the document's
   vector length (approximated as √field_len). Terms that appear in many documents (high
  df) get low IDF weights — they contribute less to the score.

  Why log TF? Raw TF gives disproportionate weight to terms that repeat many times.
  log(1+tf) dampens this — the 100th occurrence of a word adds much less value than the
  1st.

  Why smooth IDF? Standard IDF log(N/df) is undefined when df=0 and very large for rare
  terms. Adding 1 inside the log and +1 outside smooths this: log((N+1)/(df+1)) + 1.

  Why √field_len normalisation? True cosine normalisation requires computing the full L2
  norm of every document vector, which would need precomputed per-document TF-IDF
  magnitudes. Dividing by √field_len is a practical approximation that penalises longer
  documents without the overhead.

  Advantage: Rare terms in the query (like "Jabberwocky") dominate the score, giving very
  precise results for specific queries.
  Disadvantage: For common-word queries ("to be or not to be"), IDF values are near zero so
   scores are low and ranking is less reliable.

  ---
  Model 3: BM25 (bm25_search.py)

  Formula:
  IDF(t)     = log( (N - df + 0.5) / (df + 0.5) + 1 )
  TF_norm(t) = tf × (k1 + 1) / ( tf + k1 × (1 - b + b × dl/avgdl) )
  score      = Σ_field [ weight_field × Σ_t IDF(t) × TF_norm(t) ]
  Parameters: k1 = 1.5, b = 0.75 (standard values from the BM25 literature).

  What it does: BM25 (Best Match 25) is a probabilistic ranking function. It improves on
  TF-IDF in two key ways:
  1. TF saturation — the k1 parameter caps the contribution of repeated terms. Once a term
  appears enough times, more occurrences add diminishing returns. With k1=1.5, tf=10 scores
   roughly the same as tf=100.
  2. Document length normalisation — the b parameter controls how much document length
  affects scoring. With b=0.75, long documents are penalised proportionally to the average
  document length (avgdl). A rare word in a short focused document scores higher than the
  same word buried in a long book.

  Why k1=1.5 and b=0.75? These are the empirically established defaults from the original
  BM25 paper (Robertson & Sparck Jones) and have been shown to work well across many IR
  benchmarks.

  Advantage: Best overall ranking quality. Handles both short and long documents fairly.
  Widely used in production IR systems.
  Disadvantage: Slightly more complex to tune than VSM; still struggles with all-stopword
  queries due to low IDF values.

  ---
  4. Query Parsing (StructuredQueryParser)

  The parser supports field-prefixed queries:
  - title:hamlet → searches only the title field
  - author:dickens → searches only the author field
  - hamlet (no prefix) → broadcasts to all three fields

  This is shared across all three models. Unfielded terms search all fields so users don't
  need to know the field structure.

  ---
  5. Output Format

  Each model produces 6 TSV files named <query-nr>_<model-name>.tsv (e.g. 1_bm25.tsv).
  Columns:

  ┌─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │     Column      │                    Description                     │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ rank            │ Result position (1–100)                            │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ doc_id          │ Gutenberg book ID                                  │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ score           │ Model's similarity score                           │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ passage_preview │ First line in the raw book containing a query term │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ start_line      │ Line number of that passage in the file            │
  └─────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  The passage finder searches the raw .txt file line by line for any query term
  (case-insensitive) and returns the first match. This gives a concrete snippet showing why
   the document was retrieved.